<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from the </span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">North Wales Police and Crime Panel</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt"> [PCC Progress 25]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On the 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> November 2013, the Home Affairs Committee launched a new inquiry on Police and Crime Commissioners in order to examine the work and effectiveness of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> newly-created</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> statutory role that first took office on the 22</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> November 2012.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This response by the North Wales Police and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Crime Panel (NWPCP) complements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the written submissions made by the Welsh Local Government Association (WLGA) in relation to Police and Crime Panels.  However, the NWPCP wanted to reiterate the following points:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">HOLDING THE COMMISSIONER TO ACCOUNT</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">During the last year, the NWPCP has worked closely with the Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC) to develop </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a good working relationship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and whilst the NWPCP is becoming more experienced and knowledgeable, its activities to date have been mostly reactive due to the timescales involved and resources available. Whilst it is important that the NWPCP and PCC each know their own roles, it is also imperative that they understand each other’s roles and responsibilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There has been some confusion and consequent frustration around the role of a good Police and Crime Panel (PCP), particularly during the transition period.  Whilst the NWPCP has a good relationship with the PCC, the Home Office should provide clearer guidance on the role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and responsibilities of a PCP, to ensure accountability, transparency and good governance. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) has been drafted to capture the processes between the NWPCP, PCC and North Wales Police. The MoU will be designed to outline processes and procedures together with the timelines in which they are to be achieved. In addition, there has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> confusion amongst Members of the NWPCP as to the definition of ‘operational matters’, matters upon which the PCC has no remit. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An area of particular concern in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011 (Act) is the mis-match between the extensive and wide-ranging powers of the PCC and the envisaged light-touch scrutiny powers of the PCP.  In order to carry out their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> roles and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> responsibilities under the Act, it is felt that the powers the PCPs have are limited and in order to truly hold the PCC to account and provide effective challenge and scrutiny, stronger powers are required, particularly in relation to veto – a veto should mean</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> veto.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also felt that greater resources are required in order to provide effective scrutiny and challenge.  This would enable the NWPCP to be more proactive in its role and prepare a Forward Work Programme for topics that require scrutiny to allow it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gather evidence and investigate the key priorities, particularly in relation to the Police and Crime Plan and precept but also over and above its key statutory functions.  This would also help support the PCC in his role and aid the development of policies.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under the old Police A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthority reg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ime there would be a number of Sub-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommittees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with remits to scrutinise different fields of practise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> within the Police Authority. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although it is clear that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the PCC has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> set up internal performance teams, it is unclear as to how the makeup of such teams is decided, how they arrive at conclusions and who if anyone other than the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> himself can scrutinise the processes used to reach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is argued that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es are not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> transparent enough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and there should be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">acti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve role for the PCP M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">embers to observe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and scrutinise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">these new practises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Again, this links directly to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the shortage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of funding.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Earlier engagement with the PCC is needed, so that the NWPCP is made aware of the PCC’s plans and is able to scrutinise the key decisions made by the PCC. This will be particularly important when the PCC starts commissioning and decommissioning services.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst PCPs have limited powers in relation to the resolution of complaints, it has taken up a disproportionate amount of time and resources. Although detailed guidance has been produced by the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC), the lack of experience of Host Authority members of staff dealing with such complaints has led to a tentative and some-what proliferated approach to their categorisation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ENGAGEMENT</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NWPCP recognises the need to build relationships and engage with partners, particularly the Community Safety Partnerships in the future.  This would aid the development and review of priorities around the Police and Crime Plan.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NWPCP also recognises the need for greater engagement with the public, so they have an understanding of the roles and responsibilities of a PCP.  During the high profile incidents involving PCCs in the first year, there has been a profound misconception amongst the public as to the role and powers of the PCP. Webcasting and social media should be used to address this and educate the public by raising awareness of the role and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">somewhat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">limited powers of the PCP. In addition, this will make the PCPs more accountable to the public.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCPs should not work in a vacuum but work together across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in order to develop and share good practice.  The WLGA has facilitated training and de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">velopment days, which have been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of great benefit to the NWPCP together with chairing the Host Authority Officers’ Group Meeting on a quarterly basis. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NWPCP wishes to see the PCC progress with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">establishing collaboration agreements with other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCCs,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> policing org</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anisations, local authorities, partners and key stakeholders in the field of community safety, health, social care and education. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is vitally important that collaborations exist with the North West of England and on an all-Wales basis.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">LEGAL STATUS OF PCPs IN </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WALES</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Due to the stance of the Welsh Government and hence the legal status of PCPs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, its funding is limited to the Home Office Grant only. This leads to an inequality of resources as PCPs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can draw down financial contributions from the Local Authorities that fall within its Police Force Area to supplement their budget. As a consequence, it is able to deliver greater scrutiny beyond its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">statutory</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">functions.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is felt that the Act could have an adverse effect on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development of PCPs, particularly as the PCP gains more experience and focuses on their scrutiny role.  The NWPCP feels that this could limit the number of meetings per annum, which would only allow it to concentrate on its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">statutory functions, such as the precept, Plan and confirmation hearings.  In addition, limited funding is stifling the creation of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> much needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Task &amp; Finish Groups, Sub-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Committees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the triangulation of PCC evidence.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In relation to transparency, the PCC does publish Decision Notices on their website. However, again due to lack of resources, the NWPCP are reactive rather than proactive in using their general powers to request information from the PCC in relation to the Decision Notices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> e.g. method used to form conclusion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This relates to the argument for increased resources and a dedicated Scrutiny Forward Work Programme (as many PCPs’ in England have achieved due to a greater level of funding, which has enabled them to employ dedicated members of staff to support the PCP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and facilitate Task &amp; Finish Groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">). For example, scrutinising the Office of the PCC to ensure they have the appropriate number of staff together with the necessary skills and expertise to perform their statutory functions e.g. commissioning, procurement, HR and legal. This would be particularly relevant if spending on consultancy and agency fees were disproportionately high.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Home Office Grant is currently split between Administration Costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Translation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Costs and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Members’ Expenses; the NWPCP feels that the grant should not be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demarcated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but pooled, and that it be up to the individual PCP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to best determine </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how the grant is spent.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCPs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are free standing bodies, which also limits the operation of the PCPs.  Any changes to the membership have to be approved by the Home Secretary; which can be a lengthy process. As a result, nominated members have missed one or two meetings whilst the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Host Authority for NW</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCP awaits Home Secretary approval. This is not the case in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCPs currently claim their Home Office Grant on a quarterly basis, however this administrative task is very time consuming and it would be more effici</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent to claim on an annual basis.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">North Wales Police and Crime Panel</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>